The coordinator, Albino Foundation, Abia state chapter, Ugonwa Okeke has called on the members to come out from their shelves, saying nothing can stop them from achieving their life ambitions. Okeke stated this while speaking to LEADERSHIP in Umuahia, the state capital against the background of the 2020 International Albinism Awareness Day with the theme:” Made to shine against all odds.” She expressed deep concern over what she described as widespread descrimination, stigmatization, and dehumanization and brutal murder of the members across the world, appealing for attitudinal change towards them. The staff of Aba South local government council, who discosed that the chapter has a membership strength of over 175, further said they are also discriminated against for marriage and improvement opportunities in work places. According to her, even in the face of the challenges arising from COVID-19, which has affected almost everybody and sectors of the society, no individual, group, or government had found it neccessary to extend palliatives to them. She called for more public awareness on the needs and challenges of the members globally especially in Africa in line with Agenda Item 68 of the 3rd Committee of the 69th Session of the United Nations General Assemly. Okeke, who said the occasion was marked both physically and virtually, added that it included a virtual workshop and virtual launch of the “Ivory Aid Ball” Skin Cancer Trust Fund and Experience Sharing. Associating himself with the positions of the cordinator, a member of the chapter, Chuwuemeka Famous said they had came to terms with their conditions, calling for government interventions to assist them overcome them. He appealed to other members to adhere strictly to medical advice on how to protect their eyes and skin from sunlight, maintaining that the theme of the campaign could not had come at a better time than now in the country.